item.description:
【<p>For years, teams have relied on <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6</a></u> to take a more proactive approach to performance testing, ensuring they can catch issues early and deliver more reliable user experiences. That approach has helped make k6 one of the most widely used performance testing tools in the open source community today, with more than <a href="https://github.com/grafana/k6">30k stars on GitHub</a>. </p><p>Last year, we <u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/grafana-k6-1-0-release/">introduced k6 1.0</a></u>, a major release that brought TypeScript support, native extensions, revamped test insights, and production-grade stability guarantees. </p><p>Now, we’ve reached another milestone for the OSS project: <u><strong><a href="https://github.com/grafana/k6/releases">k6 2.0</a></strong></u> is generally available. </p><p>This latest release builds on k6 1.0 to better support faster, more automated software delivery lifecycles. We’ve introduced AI-assisted testing workflows, broader Playwright compatibility in the browser module, a new Assertions API, and more. Overall, the release makes it easier to author, validate, automate, and scale performance tests, especially as AI becomes a more integral part of your development workflows.</p><p>Even with these advancements, existing k6 users should still feel right at home: scripts, checks, thresholds, scenarios, and CI/CD workflows remain core to the testing experience. </p><p>Read on to learn more about what's new, and be sure to check out the <a href="https://grafana.com/events/grafanacon/agenda/ai-assisted-testing-k6-v2/">k6 2.0 talk from GrafanaCON 2026</a> in the video below. </p><h2>AI-assisted workflows for faster, scalable testing </h2><p>AI is changing how software gets written. Developers can generate, refactor, and review code faster than ever, but faster output also raises the bar for validation.</p><p>As more teams bring AI assistants into their development workflows, testing needs to become easier to author and automate, and easier for both humans and agents to interpret. k6 2.0 is built around that shift: it helps teams create tests faster, express expectations more clearly, and scale validation from local development to production-like environments.</p><p>The release includes four new commands that enable deeper integration with AI workflows and help teams use k6 programmatically:</p><ul><li><code>k6 x agent</code> helps developers bootstrap agentic testing workflows in AI coding assistants like Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, and more. It sets up the configuration, skills, and references an agent needs to use k6 to write correct, idiomatic, and modern tests; turn requirements and expectations into a testing strategy; and build out a test suite.</li></ul><ul><li><code>k6 x mcp</code> exposes k6 through a built-in <u><a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io/">Model Context Protocol</a></u> server, giving compatible agents the tools and resources they need to work effectively with k6. Agents can validate and run scripts, inspect results, iterate quickly on the tests they write, and tap into k6 resources and best practices along the way.</li><li><code>k6 x docs</code> gives agents and developers CLI access to <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6 documentation</a></u>, API references, and examples without leaving the session, or having to perform web searches.</li><li><code>k6 x explore</code> lets agents and developers browse the k6 extension registry from the CLI, filtering by type or tier and surfacing the imports, subcommands, and outputs each extension provides. Combined with <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/run/">automatic extension resolution</a></u>, agents can discover the right extension for a testing scenario and pull it into a script without leaving the session.</li></ul><p>These commands also reflect how k6 2.0 extends beyond test scripts. They are built on the same subcommand extension model now available to extension authors, which we’ll cover in the next section.</p><h2>Extensions updates to expand the reach of k6</h2><p><u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/">Extensions</a></u> help you extend core k6 functionality with new features to support your specific reliability testing needs. The 2.0 release expands on extensions in multiple ways: it provides a <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/">consolidated catalog of official and community extensions</a></u>, makes it easier to test more systems and protocols, and introduces a way to extend the k6 CLI itself.</p><h3>A curated extensions catalog</h3><p>In k6, <em>official extensions</em> are those owned and maintained by Grafana Labs, with defined compatibility expectations and support across a range of k6 versions. <em>Community extensions</em> are built and maintained by k6 contributors and members of our OSS community.</p><p>With k6 2.0, these extensions are consolidated into a <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/explore/">single catalog</a></u> that makes it easier to discover and use them, and more clearly defines the boundaries between them. Community extensions, for example, are clearly identified as community-maintained and must follow registry requirements before being included.</p><p>This distinction matters. Extensions can add new protocols, clients, outputs, and CLI workflows to k6, so teams need to understand what is maintained by Grafana Labs, what is maintained by the community, and what guarantees apply before adding an extension in their testing workflows.</p><p>The catalog also gives extension authors a clearer path to contribute. Public community extensions <a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/submit-extension/">can be submitted for inclusion</a> if they meet the registry requirements, including documentation, build instructions, usage guidance, and k6 version compatibility.</p><h3>Test more systems and protocols</h3><p>Modern systems consist of so much more than HTTP services and browser frontends. Teams also need to test databases, message queues, streaming APIs, DNS, event-driven systems, and other infrastructure components that sit on the critical path.</p><p>Official extensions maintained by Grafana Labs, including <code>k6/x/faker</code>,<code> k6/x/mqtt</code>, <code>k6/x/sql</code>, and <code>k6/x/dns</code>, sit alongside community extensions like <code>k6/x/sse</code> and <code>k6/x/kafka</code> to help with these needs. </p><p>For cataloged extensions that support automatic resolution, you can reference the extension in your script and let k6 handle the rest. For custom extensions or extensions outside automatic resolution, <u><a href="https://github.com/grafana/xk6">xk6</a></u> is still available.</p><h3>xk6 as an extension development toolbox</h3><p>Extensions are only as healthy as the tooling around them. In k6 2.0, xk6 grows from a custom k6 build tool into a full extension development toolbox.</p><p>Extension authors can scaffold a new project from official templates with <code>xk6 new</code>, build and run k6 with an in-development extension in one step, check a project against the registry's compliance requirements with <code>xk6 lint</code>, and run a suite of k6 scripts against the extension with <code>xk6 test</code>, reporting results in <u><a href="https://testanything.org/">TAP</a></u> or <u><a href="https://ctrf.io/docs/intro">CTRF JSON</a></u> for CI/CD pipelines.</p><p>The result is a shorter path from idea to a published, catalog-ready extension, and a consistent baseline of quality across official and community extensions alike.</p><h3>Subcommand extensions</h3><p>Not every extension needs to be something you import in a test script. k6 2.0 introduces <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/create/subcommand-extensions/">subcommand extensions</a></u>, a new way to add custom commands under the <code>k6 x</code> namespace.</p><p>This means teams can build workflows around test authoring, environment setup, documentation, result processing, mocks, internal tooling, or anything else they need close to the k6 runtime.</p><p>We’re already using this model internally at Grafana Labs: <code>k6 x agent</code>, <code>k6 x mcp</code>, <code>k6 x docs</code>, and <code>k6 x explore</code> are all built as subcommand extensions. The same mechanism that powers these AI-assisted workflows is now available to extension authors.</p><h2>Writing familiar browser and assertion tests</h2><p>k6 2.0 significantly expands compatibility between the <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/">k6 browser module</a></u> and the <u><a href="https://playwright.dev/">Playwright</a></u> API, making it easier for teams to apply existing browser testing knowledge  and <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/migrate-from-playwright-to-k6/">adapt existing Playwright tests to k6</a></u>.</p><p>This is important because browser testing is often where functional correctness, user experience, and performance meet. With a more familiar API surface, teams can progress  more easily from “does this user flow work?” to “how does this user flow behave under load?”</p><p>k6 2.0 also introduces a new <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6/assertions/">Assertions API</a></u>. The <code>expect()</code> API brings a Playwright-inspired assertion style to k6 scripts, with expressive matchers for both protocol and browser testing.</p><p>Assertions come in two forms:</p><ul><li><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/javascript-api/jslib/testing/non-retrying-assertions/">Non-retrying assertions</a></strong></u>, which evaluate whether a condition is true immediately. They’re useful for static values such as HTTP status codes, response headers, JSON payloads, and configuration. </li></ul><pre><code>import http from 'k6/http'; import { expect } from 'https://jslib.k6.io/k6-testing/0.6.1/index.js';
export default function () {
const response = http.get('https://quickpizza.grafana.com/');
expect(response.status).toBe(200);
expect(response.body).toBeDefined();
}
</code></pre><ul><li><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/javascript-api/jslib/testing/retrying-assertions/">Auto-retrying assertions</a></strong></u>, which hold the execution of the test until a condition becomes true or a timeout is reached. They’re especially useful for browser tests where elements may take time to appear, update, or become interactive.</li></ul><pre><code>import { browser } from 'k6/browser';
import { expect } from 'https://jslib.k6.io/k6-testing/0.6.1/index.js';
export const options = {
scenarios: {
ui: {
executor: 'shared-iterations',
options: {
browser: {
type: 'chromium'
}
},
},
},
};
export default async function () {
const page = await browser.newPage();
await page.goto('https://quickpizza.grafana.com/');
await expect(page.locator("h1")).toContainText("Welcome to QuickPizza!");
}
</code></pre><p>Assertions complement existing <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6/checks/">k6 checks</a></u>. Checks are still a great fit for load testing because they continue execution and emit metrics for threshold evaluation. Assertions are designed for use cases where a failed expectation should stop the test because the scenario is no longer valid.</p><h2>From AI-authored tests to production-scale validation</h2><p>A locally run test is a useful starting point for evaluating performance. But as teams bring testing into AI-assisted workflows and CI/CD pipelines, results need to be machine-readable and test execution needs to scale beyond a single machine.</p><p>k6 2.0 adds a new JSON summary output, making end-of-test results easier for CI/CD systems and AI agents to consume. Instead of scraping terminal output, tools can read structured results and make decisions based on them.</p><p>For real-time observability, native <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/results-output/real-time/opentelemetry/">OpenTelemetry output </a></u>makes it easier to analyze k6 results alongside the application telemetry teams already use.</p><p>And for teams that need production-scale load, <u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/2025/09/16/distributed-performance-testing-for-kubernetes-environments-grafana-k6-operator-1-0-is-here/">k6 Operator 1.0</a></u> is now stable. The operator lets teams run distributed k6 tests on Kubernetes, closer to the environments where their applications already run.</p><h2>Getting started with k6 2.0</h2><p>Here are a few ways to try k6 2.0 today:</p><ul><li><strong>Initialize:</strong> Set up AI-assisted test authoring with <code>k6 x agent</code>.</li><li><strong>Adapt:</strong> <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/migrate-from-playwright-to-k6/">Convert or migrate</a></u> existing Playwright tests with expanded browser module compatibility.</li><li><strong>Extend:</strong> Explore <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/explore/">official and community extensions</a></u> for protocols and systems beyond HTTP.</li><li><strong>Scale:</strong> Run distributed tests on Kubernetes with <u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/2025/09/16/distributed-performance-testing-for-kubernetes-environments-grafana-k6-operator-1-0-is-here/">k6 Operator 1.0</a></u></li></ul><h2>Thank you to the k6 community!</h2><p>To everyone in the community who contributed features, filed issues, fixed bugs, wrote extensions, tested early builds, or pushed for more reliable software: thank you. k6 2.0 would not be possible without you.</p><p>You can learn more in our <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6 documentation</a></u>, and we’d love to hear what you think on <u><a href="https://github.com/grafana/k6">GitHub</a></u>.</p><p>Happy testing!</p><p><em><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/?pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Grafana Cloud</a></em><em> is the easiest way to get started with Grafana k6 and performance testing. We have a generous forever-free tier and plans for every use case. </em><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user/?src=k6io&redirectPath=k6&pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Sign up for free now!</a></em></u></p>】<p>多年来，团队一直依靠 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6</a></u> 采取更主动的方法进行性能测试，确保他们能够及早发现问题并提供更可靠的用户体验。这种方法使 k6 成为当今开源社区中使用最广泛的性能测试工具之一，在 GitHub 上拥有超过 30k 颗星</a>。 </p><p>去年，我们<u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/grafana-k6-1-0-release/">推出了 k6 1.0</a></u>，这是一个主要版本，带来了 TypeScript 支持、本机扩展、改进的测试见解和生产级稳定性保证。 </p><p>现在，我们的 OSS 项目达到了另一个里程碑：<u><strong><a href="https://github.com/grafana/k6/releases">k6 2.0</a></strong></u> 正式发布。 </p><p>这个最新版本基于 k6 1.0 构建，以更好地支持更快、更自动化的软件交付生命周期。我们引入了人工智能辅助测试工作流程、浏览器模块中更广泛的 Playwright 兼容性、新的断言 API 等等。总体而言，该版本使编写、验证、自动化和扩展性能测试变得更加容易，特别是当人工智能成为开发工作流程中更不可或缺的一部分时。</p><p>即使有了这些进步，现有的 k6 用户仍然应该感到宾至如归：脚本、检查、阈值、场景和 CI/CD 工作流程仍然是测试体验的核心。 </p><p>继续阅读以了解有关新功能的更多信息，请务必观看下面视频中的 <a href="https://grafana.com/events/grafanacon/agenda/ai-assisted-testing-k6-v2/">GrafanaCON 2026 的 k6 2.0 演讲</a>。 </p><h2>人工智能辅助工作流程可实现更快、可扩展的测试</h2><p>人工智能正在改变软件的编写方式。开发人员可以比以往更快地生成、重构和审查代码，但更快的输出也提高了验证的门槛。</p><p>随着越来越多的团队将 AI 助手引入其开发工作流程，测试需要变得更容易编写和自动化，并且更易于人类和代理解释。 k6 2.0 就是围绕这一转变而构建的：它帮助团队更快地创建测试、更清楚地表达期望，并将验证从本地开发扩展到类似生产的环境。</p><p>该版本包括四个新命令，可实现与 AI 工作流程的更深入集成，并帮助团队以编程方式使用 k6：</p><ul><li><code>k6 x agent</code> 帮助开发人员在 Claude Code、Codex、Cursor 等 AI 编码助手中引导代理测试工作流程。它设置了代理使用 k6 编写正确的、惯用的和现代的测试所需的配置、技能和参考；将需求和期望转化为测试策略；并构建一个测试套件。</li></ul><ul><li><code>k6 x mcp</code>通过内置<u><a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io/">模型上下文协议</a></u>服务器公开k6，为兼容的代理提供他们所需的工具和资源与 k6 有效合作。代理可以验证和运行脚本、检查结果、快速迭代他们编写的测试，并在此过程中利用 k6 资源和最佳实践。</li><li><code>k6 x docs</code> 使代理和开发人员能够通过 CLI 访问 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6 文档</a></u>、API 参考和示例，而无需离开会话或执行 Web搜索。</li><li><code>k6 x explore</code> 让代理和开发人员可以从 CLI 浏览 k6 扩展注册表，按类型或层进行过滤，并显示每个扩展提供的导入、子命令和输出。与<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/run/">自动扩展解析</a></u>相结合，代理可以发现测试场景的正确扩展并将其拉入脚本而无需离开会话。</li></ul><p>这些命令还反映了 k6 2.0 如何扩展到测试脚本之外。它们基于现在可供扩展作者使用的相同子命令扩展模型构建，我们将在下一节中介绍。</p><h2>扩展更新以扩大 k6 的范围</h2><p><u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/">扩展</a></u>帮助您使用新功能扩展核心 k6 功能，以支持您的特定可靠性测试需求。 2.0 版本以多种方式扩展了扩展：它提供了<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/">官方和社区扩展的综合目录</a></u>，使测试更多系统和协议变得更加容易，并引入了扩展 k6 CLI 本身的方法。</p><h3>精心策划的扩展目录</h3><p>在 k6 中，<em>官方扩展是由 Grafana Labs 拥有和维护的扩展，具有明确的兼容性期望和跨一系列 k6 版本的支持。 <em>社区扩展</em>由 k6 贡献者和我们 OSS 社区的成员构建和维护。</p><p>在 k6 2.0 中，这些扩展被合并到<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/explore/">单一目录</a></u>中，这样可以更轻松地发现和使用它们，并更清晰地定义它们之间的界限。例如，社区扩展被明确标识为社区维护的，并且在包含之前必须遵循注册表要求。</p><p>这种区别很重要。扩展可以向 k6 添加新协议、客户端、输出和 CLI 工作流程，因此团队需要了解 Grafana Labs 维护的内容、社区维护的内容以及在测试工作流程中添加扩展之前适用的保证。</p><p>该目录还为扩展作者提供了更清晰的贡献路径。如果公共社区扩展符合注册表要求，包括文档、构建说明、使用指南和 k6 版本兼容性，<a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/submit-extension/">可以提交纳入</a>。</p><h3>测试更多系统ms 和协议</h3><p>现代系统不仅仅包含 HTTP 服务和浏览器前端。团队还需要测试数据库、消息队列、流 API、DNS、事件驱动系统以及关键路径上的其他基础设施组件。</p><p>Grafana Labs 维护的官方扩展，包括 <code>k6/x/faker</code>、<code> k6/x/mqtt</code>、<code>k6/x/sql</code> 和 <code>k6/x/dns</code> 与社区扩展一起使用，例如<code>k6/x/sse</code> 和 <code>k6/x/kafka</code> 来帮助满足这些需求。 </p><p>对于支持自动解析的编目扩展，您可以在脚本中引用该扩展，然后让 k6 处理其余的事情。对于自定义扩展或自动解析之外的扩展，<u><a href="https://github.com/grafana/xk6">xk6</a></u> 仍然可用。</p><h3>xk6 作为扩展开发工具箱</h3><p>扩展的健康程度取决于其周围的工具。在 k6 2.0 中，xk6 从自定义 k6 构建工具发展成为完整的扩展开发工具箱。</p><p>扩展作者可以使用 <code>xk6 new</code> 从官方模板构建新项目，使用正在开发的扩展一步构建和运行 k6，使用 <code>xk6 lint</code> 检查项目是否符合注册表的合规性要求，并使用 <code>xk6 针对扩展运行一套 k6 脚本测试</code>，以 <u><a href="https://testanything.org/">TAP</a></u> 或 <u><a href="https://ctrf.io/docs/intro">CTRF JSON</a></u> 的形式报告 CI/CD 管道的结果。</p><p>结果是从想法到已发布、可用于目录的扩展的更短路径，以及跨官方和社区扩展的一致质量基线类似。</p><h3>子命令扩展</h3><p>并非每个扩展都需要是您在测试脚本中导入的内容。 k6 2.0 引入了<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/create/subcommand-extensions/">子命令扩展</a></u>，这是一种在 <code>k6 x</code> 命名空间下添加自定义命令的新方法。</p><p>这意味着团队可以围绕测试创作、环境设置、文档、结果处理、模拟、内部工具或他们需要的任何其他内容构建工作流程接近 k6 运行时。</p><p>我们已经在 Grafana Labs 内部使用此模型：<code>k6 x agent</code>、<code>k6 x mcp</code>、<code>k6 x docs</code> 和 <code>k6 x explore</code> 均构建为子命令扩展。现在，扩展作者可以使用为这些 AI 辅助工作流程提供支持的相同机制。</p><h2>编写熟悉的浏览器和断言测试</h2><p>k6 2.0 显着扩展了 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/">k6 浏览器模块</a></u> 和 <u><a 之间的兼容性href="https://playwright.dev/">Playwright</a></u> API，使团队能够更轻松地应用现有的浏览器测试知识，并<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/migrate-from-playwright-to-k6/">调整现有的 Playwright 测试以适应 k6</a></u>。</p><p>这很重要，因为浏览器测试通常是功能正确性、用户体验和性能的结合点。借助更熟悉的 API 界面，团队可以更轻松地解决“此用户流程是否有效？”的问题。 “此用户流在负载下的行为如何？”</p><p>k6 2.0 还引入了新的 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6/assertions/">断言 API</a></u>。 <code>expect()</code> API 为 k6 脚本带来了受 Playwright 启发的断言风格，并为协议和浏览器测试提供了富有表现力的匹配器。</p><p>断言有两种形式：</p><ul><li><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/javascript-api/jslib/testing/non-retrying-assertions/">非重试断言</a></strong></u>，它评估条件是否立即为真。它们对于静态值非常有用，例如 HTTP 状态代码、响应标头、JSON 负载和配置。 </li></ul><pre><code>从'k6/http'导入http；从'https://jslib.k6.io/k6-testing/0.6.1/index.js'导入{expect}；
导出默认函数 () {
const 响应 = http.get('https://quickpizza.grafana.com/');
期望(响应.状态).toBe(200);
期望(response.body).toBeDefined();
}
</code></pre><ul><li><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/javascript-api/jslib/testing/retrying-assertions/">自动重试断言</a></strong></u>，它会保持测试的执行，直到条件变为真或达到超时。它们对于浏览器测试特别有用，其中元素可能需要一些时间才能出现、更新或变为交互式。</li></ul><pre><code>import { browser } from 'k6/browser';
从'https://jslib.k6.io/k6-testing/0.6.1/index.js'导入{expect}；
导出常量选项= {
场景：{
用户界面：{
执行者：'共享迭代'，
选项：{
浏览器：{
类型：“铬”
}
},
},
},
};
导出默认异步函数 () {
const page = 等待 browser.newPage();
等待 page.goto('https://quickpizza.grafana.com/');
等待期望（page.locator（“h1”））。toContainText（“欢迎来到QuickPizza！”）;
}
</code></pre><p>断言补充了现有的<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6/checks/">k6 检查</a></u>。检查仍然非常适合负载测试，因为它们会继续执行并发出阈值评估指标。断言是为预期失败而停止测试的用例而设计的，因为场景不再有效。</p><h2>从 AI 编写的测试到生产规模验证</h2><p>本地运行的测试是评估性能的有用起点。但随着团队将测试引入人工智能辅助工作流程和 CI/CD 管道，结果需要是机器可读的，并且测试执行需要扩展到单台机器之外。</p><p>k6 2.0 添加了新的 JSON 摘要输出，使 CI/CD 系统和 AI 代理更容易使用测试结束结果。工具可以读取结构化结果并根据它们做出决策，而不是抓取终端输出。</p><p>对于重新实时可观测性，原生<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/results-output/real-time/opentelemetry/">OpenTelemetry 输出</a></u>使分析 k6 结果以及遥测团队已经使用的应用程序变得更加容易。</p><p>对于需要生产规模负载的团队，<u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/2025/09/16/distributed-performance-testing-for-kubernetes-environments-grafana-k6-operator-1-0-is-here/">k6 Operator 1.0</a></u> 现已稳定。 Operator 允许团队在 Kubernetes 上运行分布式 k6 测试，更接近其应用程序已运行的环境。</p><h2>开始使用 k6 2.0</h2><p>以下是立即尝试 k6 2.0 的几种方法：</p><ul><li><strong>初始化：</strong>使用 <code>k6 x 设置 AI 辅助测试编写代理</code>。</li><li><strong>适应：</strong> <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/using-k6-browser/migrate-from-playwright-to-k6/">转换或迁移</a></u>现有的 Playwright 测试，并扩展浏览器模块兼容性。</li><li><strong>扩展：</strong>探索<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/extensions/explore/">针对 HTTP 之外的协议和系统的官方和社区扩展</a></u>。</li><li><strong>规模：</strong>使用 <u><a 在 Kubernetes 上运行分布式测试href="https://grafana.com/blog/2025/09/16/distributed-performance-testing-for-kubernetes-environments-grafana-k6-operator-1-0-is-here/">k6 Operator 1.0</a></u></li></ul><h2>感谢 k6 社区！</h2><p>感谢社区中贡献功能、提交问题、修复错误、写道的每个人扩展、测试早期版本或推动更可靠的软件：谢谢。没有您，k6 2.0 就不可能实现。</p><p>您可以在我们的 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/">k6 文档</a></u>中了解更多信息，我们很想听听您在 <u><a href="https://github.com/grafana/k6">GitHub</a></u> 上的想法。</p><p>快乐测试！</p><p><em><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/?pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Grafana Cloud</a></em><em>是开始使用 Grafana k6 和性能测试的最简单方法。我们为每个用例提供慷慨的永久免费套餐和计划。 </em><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user/?src=k6io&redirectPath=k6&pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">立即免费注册！</a></em></u></p>

【<p>To simulate real user behavior, performance tests often rely on API keys, tokens, or credentials to interact with real systems. But as your testing suite grows, this sensitive data can start to sprawl across scripts, configs, and environments, increasing the risk of exposure and making tests harder to manage and maintain. </p><p>To address this challenge, we’re rolling out <strong>secrets management for </strong><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/k6/?pg=performance-testing-best-practices-how-to-prepare-for-peak-demand-with-grafana-cloud-k6&plcmt=in-text">Grafana Cloud k6</a></strong></u>, the fully managed performance testing platform powered by k6 OSS. Secrets management allows you to securely store and use sensitive values in your load tests. This means if your tests rely on API tokens, credentials, or any other confidential data, you no longer need to hardcode them into your scripts or pass them around manually.</p><p>With secrets management, secrets are stored centrally in Grafana Cloud and injected into your tests at runtime. This keeps your scripts clean, avoids accidental leaks in version control, and makes it easier to reuse the same test across environments. </p><p>Here’s a look at how to get started. </p><h2>Getting started: How to manage secrets from the Grafana Cloud UI</h2><p>Secrets can be created and managed directly from the Grafana Cloud web UI. To access them, navigate to <strong>Testing & synthetics</strong> > <strong>Performance</strong> > <strong>Settings</strong>, and open the <strong>Secrets</strong> tab from the menu.</p><p>From this interface, you can perform all the basic lifecycle operations:</p><ul><li><strong>Create secrets</strong> by providing a name, description, and value. The name is how the secret will be referenced in your tests, and the value is the sensitive data itself. Once saved, the secret becomes immediately available to your tests. For each secret, you can also write a description (e.g., to explain the secret’s purpose) and use labels to help with organization.</li><li><strong>Edit secrets</strong> to modify their values, descriptions, or labels. Note that editing a secret does not reveal its current value; instead, you provide a new value that replaces the previous one. This ensures that secrets are never exposed through the UI after they are initially set. If you need to rotate credentials, you can simply overwrite the existing secret with a new value.</li><li><strong>Delete secrets</strong> that are no longer needed.</li></ul><p>A key design principle here is that <strong>secret values are write-only in the UI</strong>. After creation, they cannot be read back or displayed. This prevents accidental exposure through screenshots, screen sharing, or casual inspection, and aligns with common security practices.</p><h2>Using secrets in your Grafana Cloud k6 tests</h2><p>Once your secrets are defined, using them in your tests is simple. Grafana Cloud k6 provides a dedicated module, <code>k6/secrets</code>, which allows you to retrieve secret values at runtime.</p><p>You can import the module and access a secret by its name:</p><p></p><pre><code>import check from "k6";
import http from 'k6/http';
import secrets from 'k6/secrets';
export default async function main () {
const apiToken = await secrets.get('api-token');
const headers = {
Authorization: `Bearer ${apiToken}`,
};
console.log("Headers: " + JSON.stringify(headers))
let res = http.get('https://example.com/api', {headers: headers});
check(res, { "get executions status is 200": (res) => res.status === 200 });
}
</code></pre><p>In this example, the secret "api-token" is fetched when the test runs and used as part of an HTTP request. From the script's perspective, the returned value behaves like a regular string, so you can use it anywhere you would normally use a variable.</p><p>This makes it easy to integrate secrets into existing scripts without major refactoring. You can gradually replace hardcoded values or environment variables with secrets managed in Grafana Cloud.</p><p>Secrets are also protected during test execution. If a secret is accidentally logged, its value will not be exposed in the logs. Instead, it will be redacted automatically. This reduces the risk of leaking sensitive data through debugging output or test results. Combined with write-only storage in the UI, this ensures that secrets remain protected throughout their lifecycle: from creation, to usage in tests, to observability outputs.</p><h2>Learn more </h2><p>Secrets management in Grafana Cloud k6 is available now in public preview. The feature is also <u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/how-to-create-and-manage-secrets-with-grafana-cloud-synthetic-monitoring">generally available in Grafana Cloud Synthetic Monitoring</a></u>, a black box monitoring solution powered by k6 that lets you proactively assess system reliability and performance.</p><p>To learn more, please visit our <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/grafana-cloud/testing/k6/author-run/manage-secrets/">documentation</a></u>. </p><p><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/?pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Grafana Cloud</a></em></u><em> is the easiest way to get started with k6 and performance testing. We have a generous forever-free tier and plans for every use case. </em><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user/?src=k6io&redirectPath=k6&pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Sign up for free now!</a></em></u> </p>】<p>为了模拟真实的用户行为，性能测试通常依赖 API 密钥、令牌或凭据与真实系统进行交互。但随着测试套件的增长，这些敏感数据可能开始跨脚本、配置和环境蔓延，从而增加暴露的风险，并使测试更难以管理和维护。 </p><p>为了应对这一挑战，我们正在推出<strong>秘密管理</strong><u><strong><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/k6/?pg=performance-testing-best-practices-how-to-prepare-for-peak-demand-with-grafana-cloud-k6&plcmt=in-text">Grafana Cloud k6</a></strong></u>，由 k6 OSS 提供支持的完全托管的性能测试平台。机密管理允许您在负载测试中安全地存储和使用敏感值。这意味着，如果您的测试依赖于 API 令牌、凭据或任何其他机密数据，您不再需要将它们硬编码到脚本中或手动传递它们。</p><p>通过机密管理，机密将集中存储在 Grafana Cloud 中，并在运行时注入到您的测试中。这可以保持脚本干净，避免版本控制中的意外泄漏，并且可以更轻松地跨环境重用相同的测试。 </p><p>以下是如何开始。 </p><h2>入门：如何从 Grafana Cloud UI 管理机密</h2><p>可以直接从 Grafana Cloud Web UI 创建和管理机密。要访问它们，请导航至<strong>测试和合成</strong> > <strong>性能</strong> > <strong>设置</strong>，然后从菜单中打开<strong>机密</strong>选项卡。</p><p>在此界面中，您可以执行所有基本生命周期操作：</p><ul><li><strong>通过提供名称、描述和值创建机密</strong>。名称是在测试中引用机密的方式，值是敏感数据本身。保存后，该秘密将立即可供您的测试使用。对于每个秘密，您还可以编写描述（例如，解释秘密的用途）并使用标签来帮助组织。</li><li><strong>编辑秘密</strong>以修改其值、描述或标签。请注意，编辑机密不会泄露其当前值；相反，您提供一个新值来替换前一个值。这可确保秘密在最初设置后永远不会通过 UI 暴露。如果您需要轮换凭据，只需用新值覆盖现有密钥即可。</li><li><strong>删除不再需要的密钥</strong>。</li></ul><p>这里的一个关键设计原则是<strong>密钥值在 UI 中是只写的</strong>。创建后，它们无法读回或显示。这可以防止通过屏幕截图、屏幕共享或临时检查意外泄露，并符合常见的安全实践。</p><h2>在 Grafana Cloud k6 测试中使用机密</h2><p>定义机密后，在测试中使用它们就很简单。 Grafana Cloud k6 提供了专用的模块 <code>k6/secrets</code>，它允许您在运行时检索机密值。</p><p>您可以导入模块并通过其名称访问机密：</p><p></p><pre><code>import check from "k6";
从'k6/http'导入http；
从“k6/secrets”导入机密；
导出默认异步函数 main () {
const apiToken =等待secrets.get('api-token');
常量标头 = {
授权：`不记名${apiToken}`，
};
console.log("标题：" + JSON.stringify(标题))
让 res = http.get('https://example.com/api', {headers: headers});
check(res, { "获取执行状态为 200": (res) => res.status === 200 });
}
</code></pre><p>在此示例中，测试运行时会获取秘密“api-token”并将其用作 HTTP 请求的一部分。从脚本的角度来看，返回值的行为类似于常规字符串，因此您可以在通常使用变量的任何地方使用它。</p><p>这使得可以轻松地将机密集成到现有脚本中，而无需进行重大重构。您可以逐步使用 Grafana Cloud 中管理的机密替换硬编码值或环境变量。</p><p>机密在测试执行期间也会受到保护。如果意外记录了机密，则其值不会在日志中公开。相反，它将被自动编辑。这降低了通过调试输出或测试结果泄露敏感数据的风险。与 UI 中的只写存储相结合，这可确保机密在其整个生命周期中始终受到保护：从创建到测试中的使用，再到可观察性输出。</p><h2>了解更多信息</h2><p>Grafana Cloud k6 中的机密管理现已推出公共预览版。该功能还<u><a href="https://grafana.com/blog/how-to-create-and-manage-secrets-with-grafana-cloud-synthetic-monitoring">在 Grafana Cloud Synthetic Monitoring 中普遍可用</a></u>，这是一种由 k6 提供支持的黑盒监控解决方案，可让您主动评估系统可靠性和性能。</p><p>要了解更多信息，请访问我们的<u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/grafana-cloud/testing/k6/author-run/manage-secrets/">文档</a></u>。 </p><p><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/?pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">Grafana Cloud</a></em></u><em>是开始进行 k6 和性能测试的最简单方法。我们为每个用例提供慷慨的永久免费套餐和计划。 </em><u><em><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user/?src=k6io&redirectPath=k6&pg=blog&plcmt=body-txt">立即免费注册！</a></em></u> </p>
